her for the first time the full story of the orange industry—how growers, scientists, and workers transformed the natural and social landscape of California, turning it into a factory for the production of millions of oranges. That industry put up billboards in cities across the nation and placed enticing pictures of sun-kissed fruits into nearly every American's home. It convinced Americans that oranges could be consumed as embodiments of pure nature and talismans of good health. But, as this book shows, the tables were turned during the Great Depression when Upton Sinclair, Carey McWilliams, Dorothea Lange, and John Steinbeck made the Orange Empire into a symbol of what was wrong with America's relationship to nature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOrange industryzCaliforniaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a20th century american culture.  a20th century american literature.  aadvertising.  aamerican labor.  aamerican literature.  acalifornia.  acalifornian culture.  acalifornian history.  acalifornian oranges.  acalifornian society.  acarey mcwilliams.  acorporations.  ademocracy.  adiplomacy.  adorothea lange.  aenvironmental justice.  afood.  agovernment and governing.  agrapes of wrath.  agreat depression.  ajohn steinbeck.  alabor.  anature.  aorange industry.  aoranges.  athe epic campaign.  athe sunkist campaign.  aupton sinclair.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023886240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094089540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940895/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of C